                    """ Background Origin of the Hadiya people  
              
              There are two dominant views about the origin of Hadiya people. From these views the first one argued that Hadiya people are indigenous people of south central Ethiopia. According to oral traditions of Hadiya people; the name Hadiya comes from the combination of two words, Hada and iyya. Hada refers many and iyya refers carry so that the name Hadiya refers the one who carry many. It shows the tolerance and hospitality nature of the people as well as other ethno linguistic groups living with them. 1
              The second argument related with the origin of Hadiya people grouped them with Arab descendants. The name Hadiya in Arabic word refers gift. Accordingly, this group believed that Arab peninsula as the birth place of Hadiya people.Ulrich Braukamper, a German historian and writer argued that Hadiya people come from Arab before two thousand years ago and intermingled with east African Cushitic speaking communities. He also explained that the neighbouring people of Hadiya call them in different ways. For instance, Arsi as Hadiya means the one who receive holy word from Prophet Mohammed or the owners of the land. Added to this, the people around Chercher considered as Hadiya as they left over or remnant to show as not involved in the migration and Jihad warriors called Hadiya as gift.2It needs further study.
               According to its geographical location Hadiya zone located south of Gurage zone, south west of Wolaita zone, north of Kambata-Tambaro zone, and east of Gibe River and Yem special Worada. The Hadiya is capital town, Hossana is found at 232 Km south of Addis Ababa.3The 1994 national census reported a total population
                for Hadiya Zone of 1,050,151, of whom 521,807 were men and 528,344 women; 67,705 or 6.45% of its population were urban dwellers at the time. The five largest ethnic groups reported in Hadiya were the Hadiya (78.16%), the Silte (10.13%), the Kembata (2.22%), the SoddoGurage (1.8%), and the Amhara (1.63%); all other ethnic groups made up 6.06% of the population.4Based on the 2007 Census conducted by the CSA, this Zone has a total population of 1,231,196, of whom 612,026 are men and 619,170 women; with an area of 3,593.31 square kilometres, Hadiya has a population density of 342.64. While 134,041 or 10.89% are urban inhabitants, a further 157 individuals are pastoralists.5
              
               Language of Hadiya
              
              Hadiya people have their own language called hadiyyisa (hadiyigna in Amharic).It belongs to Afrio Asiatic super family,and it is South highland Cushitic language group. Although, majority of the people are speaking hadiyyisa, other languages such as Amharic, Kebetisa, Woleyto, and Gurage are spoken by the people.6 It has gradual history of development and now days they are using it for local communication, schooling and in Hossana and WolikteFm 95.6 and 89.2 frequencies respectively.
                
                Religion of Hadiya 
              
                From early emergence Hadiya people were followers of different religions .They worshiped both polytheistic and monotheistic religions phases. The indigenous religion of Hadiya is called fandanano .The majority followers were fandano and their religion has an Islamic type of symmetry called fandanima(religious process or ceremony).This religion assumed as it began by two individuals namely, Itto and Alibejo  from the Bimado clan. However, in the first half of 19thC this religion declined due to introduction of modern (monotheistic religions) the Islam and Christianity.8
              After time underwent Hadiya moved from polytheistic to monotheistic. According to different sources Islam was the earliest monotheistic religion worshiped by Hadiya. In 13thc almost all Hadiya garads (local chiefs) become Muslims. Islam introduced to Hadiya by peaceful means that means through marriage and trade .on the other hand Hadiya embraced to Islam because of conquest during the war of expansion and war of Ahmed IbnIbriham al Gaz very small minorities converted to Islam. Even today about 5% of Hadiya are muslims.9 
              Beginning from 15th century Orthodox Christianity become one of worshiped religion among Hadiya people .Orthodox Christianity introduced to the region from Christian highland by the people of masmas who are Amhara ethnic group live in Hadiya zone. Today about 13% of Hadiya are followers of Orthodox Christianity and it highly expanded during Menelik II Conquest.10By 1920s protestant Christianity introduced to Hadiya and after decade most of people become protestant Christians. Today about 80% of Hadiya are Christians. Hadiya are also followers of Catholic religion, it introduced and spread during Italians occupation by Italians from 1936-1941.Today about 1.5% of Hadiya are Catholics and the rest are traditional religion practicers.11Therefore, Hadiya worshiped different religion and all religious societies live together with peace, tolerance and marriage interlink is also common as well as no room for conflict because of religious diversit
               
               Economy of Hadiya
              
              Ancient Hadiya people were pastoralists in that they herd cattle in movable way and in latter periods they engaged in agriculture that means in crop production and herding of animals. As many sources argued that beginning from the time of slave trade, they involved in small scale trade. Now day’s diaspora income also become skeleton for the economy of the people.
              r
              Traditional Administration of Hadiya
              
              For long period of time Hadiya people ruled by traditional administrative system called garad system, for political, economic, social and cultural purposes. In general garad means highly respected person in the society and as title it also given for rich or cattle owner. The garad system was more of quit egalitarian, undemocratic and characterized by absence of central administration but it guided the society traditionally and based on personal will and elders order.13In order to be garad there is no guideline but it was assumed that he had to be orator, good in personal quality and ethics, wisdom, eloquence, problem solving and skill of negotiation, dignified, hospitality, decision making ability, acceptable with in society and who was well enough to draft traditional laws that guide the society .In addition, garad come to position hereditarily. Garad of Hadiya played different socio-economic and political roles with in the society. For instance, they played greater role in solving controversies ,demarcating boundaries, declaring war, collecting tribute, distributing land, drafting laws, made relations with neighbours, call meting and others.14
               
